es to reveal the complex challenges liberated victims faced and the daunting tasks their liberators undertook to help them reclaim their shattered lives. Historian Dan Stone focuses on the survivors—their feelings of guilt, exhaustion, fear, shame for having survived, and devastating grief for lost family members; their immense medical problems; and their later demands to be released from Displaced Persons camps and resettled in countries of their own choosing. Stone also tracks the efforts of British, American, Canadian, and Russian liberators as they contended with survivors’ immediate needs, then grappled with longer-term issues that shaped the postwar world and ushered in the first chill of the Cold War years ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConcentration campszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945). 0aNazi concentration campszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aNazi concentration campszEuropexHistory. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration campsxLiberation. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJews. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xRefugees. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030020457540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300216035?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300216035423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300216035/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY